All vulnerabilities involve the same root cause: When a 303 redirect occurs, the HTTP method is changed to GET, but the request body is NOT cleared before making the redirect request. This causes sensitive POST data to be sent with a GET request to the redirect location, violating CWE-200 (Exposure of Sensitive Information to an Unauthorized Actor).

The vulnerability is exploitable when:
- An attacker controls or compromises a server to send a 303 redirect response
- The original request contains sensitive data in the body (form data, JSON, credentials, etc.)
- The redirect location is attacker-controlled or on a different host
- The sensitive body data is leaked to the redirect destination
